- `Persistent`allocators persist indefinitely. These are the slowest allocations that take the most time to execute. Typically these are created during`OnCreate`, not`OnUpdate`.

To properly dispose of a`TempJob`or`Persistent`allocation, you will want to call the`Dispose`method on the collection, typically during the`OnDestroy`method for`Persistent`allocations, and at the end of`OnUpdate`for`TempJob`allocations. To ensure that you don't inadvertently dispose of an allocation that's still needed, you can pass a job's`JobHandle`to the`Dispose`method to ensure that the allocation persists until the job is finished using it. That way, you avoid scenarios such as attempting to access indexes of a`NativeList`or`NativeArray`that has already been disposed of.

